<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_dictionary` row that
    declares the `type` Choice field on the `x_casemgmt_case` custom table
    inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim):
        Field   Type            Constraints
        type    Choice          General Inquiry, Complaint - extensible

    Per AAP Section 0.4.4 the case-submission portal page populates this field
    as one of the five user-supplied inputs (subject, type, description,
    requester_name, requester_email).

    Per AAP Section 0.5.5 the value of this field is the discriminator that
    selects which Flow Designer state-machine flow handles a case's lifecycle
    transitions:
       - ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml triggers on type=General Inquiry
       - ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml      triggers on type=Complaint
    Each flow's OnUpdate trigger filter compares against the choice LABEL
    string, so the labels declared in ../choices/sys_choice_case_type.xml
    MUST match the trigger filter strings literally.

    This dictionary entry ONLY declares that the `type` Choice field exists on
    the parent table. The choice values themselves (General Inquiry, Complaint)
    are authored as separate sys_choice records in
    ../choices/sys_choice_case_type.xml. This separation is intentional and
    matches AAP Section 0.5.7's "extensible" qualifier - new case types can
    later be added by appending sys_choice rows (and authoring a new state-
    machine flow per type) WITHOUT altering this dictionary entry.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 134-135:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_type")
            private String caseType;
        ArkCase's `caseType` was a free-form String column on the
        `acm_case_file` JPA entity - any caller could write any string and
        the JPA layer enforced no enumeration. This was acceptable in
        ArkCase only because the case-type discriminator was effectively
        the JPA SINGLE_TABLE inheritance class-name (`cm_class_name`),
        not the `cm_case_type` column. The ServiceNow target inverts that
        coupling: the dedicated `type` Choice field IS the type
        discriminator, and ServiceNow scoped applications do not use JPA
        single-table-inheritance class-name discriminators. Constraining
        the field to a Choice rather than a free-form String prevents
        typos, enforces flow-routing correctness, and makes the Manager
        View dashboard's "All cases by type" donut chart (per
        ../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_type.xml) deterministic.
      - The field name is `type` (lowercase, 4 chars; NOT `case_type`,
        NOT `caseType`) per AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim. This matches
        the conventional ServiceNow Choice-field naming convention
        across the platform (incident.category, sc_request.priority,
        change_request.type, etc.).

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: `<name>` resolves to `x_casemgmt_case`
        within the scoped application, and `<sys_scope>` / `<sys_package>`
        bind THIS dictionary record to the same scope by `source` attribute
        lookup. NO global-scope writes - the OOB tables `task`, `incident`,
        `sys_user`, etc. are never modified.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_casemgmt`), not by literal sys_id. The `<sys_id>`
        text-node value is THIS record's own deterministic primary key
        (MD5 of the canonical field identifier `x_casemgmt_case.type`)
        and is NOT a reference to any other record.
      - The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention;
        ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the
        scope id must be concrete in the XML before export.
      - mandatory=false at the dictionary level per AAP Section 0.5.7
        verbatim ("type | Choice | General Inquiry, Complaint -
        extensible" - no Mandatory marker) and AAP Section 0.7.1
        strict-literal "no additions, no renames, no type relaxations"
        rule. The AAP authoritative text takes precedence over the
        functional argument that the per-case-type flows in AAP
        Section 0.5.5 require this discriminator: if a case is
        inserted without a `type`, neither flow's OnUpdate trigger
        will match and the case will simply have no automated
        lifecycle - which is acceptable POC behavior since manual
        status writes are still possible. Internal-form callers,
        Table API consumers, the scripted REST submission endpoint
        per ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_casemgmt_case_submit.xml,
        and the synthetic seed cases per
        ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_*.xml all continue
        to populate this field explicitly with one of the two
        supported labels (General Inquiry or Complaint), so the
        absence of a dictionary-level mandatory constraint does not
        in practice produce empty `type` values. If a future
        requirement makes type strictly mandatory, AAP Section 0.5.7
        will be updated first and this dictionary entry will follow.
      - read_only=false: an internal user (case_manager) editing the case
        record may correct an erroneous type assignment. The corresponding
        flow filter changes are picked up by the platform on the next
        OnUpdate trigger evaluation - no schema migration required.
      - default_value is EMPTY (no implicit default) per AAP Section 0.5.7
        and the agent prompt's Phase 4 verbatim. Defaulting silently to
        either "General Inquiry" or "Complaint" would skew the Manager
        View "All cases by type" donut analytics by inflating whichever
        type happened to be the default. The user MUST explicitly choose,
        either through the internal form, the external portal page,
        or the scripted REST request payload.
      - audit=false: the field tracks a categorical attribute, not a
        regulated identifier. Per AAP Section 0.7.2 this POC is scoped
        to functional capability, not full audit-trail compliance.
      - max_length 40 is generous: the longest defined label is
        "General Inquiry" (15 chars). The 40-char headroom accommodates
        future extensible labels (e.g., "Internal Investigation",
        "Third-Party Inquiry") without a schema migration.
      - choice 3 = "Choice list, no description column" - the standard
        Choice-field configuration when a sibling sys_choice record set
        defines the allowed values.
      - No reference target: this is a String-backed Choice field, not a
        Reference field. All `<reference*>` elements are empty and
        `<table_reference>false</table_reference>`.
      - No PII: the field stores only categorical labels chosen from a
        controlled vocabulary; no real names, email addresses, or
        organizational identifiers are derived from or stored in this
        column.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      - This record MUST load AFTER `../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml`
        (parent table), since `<name>x_casemgmt_case</name>` references
        the table by name.
      - This record MUST load BEFORE the consumers that read or write
        the `type` column:
          * ../choices/sys_choice_case_type.xml (the choice values
            General Inquiry and Complaint, which reference this
            dictionary entry by `name` + `element` lookup)
          * ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml (OnUpdate trigger
            filtered by `type=General Inquiry`)
          * ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml (OnUpdate trigger
            filtered by `type=Complaint`)
          * ../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_type.xml (donut chart
            grouped by this field)
          * ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_casemgmt_case_submit.xml
            (writes this field on portal-originated case submissions)
          * ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_*.xml (synthetic demo
            cases that must populate this field to satisfy AAP Section
            0.7.4 minimum-data thresholds: "both case types represented")
-->
<record_update table="sys_dictionary">
    <sys_dictionary action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <array>false</array>
